data.message: Congratulations, everyone! You have all gotten through the 90 days of posts in this study. Look out for an email from us that will tell you how you can get a $20 gift card by filling out our 3 month check in survey. This is the 2nd out of 4 surveys and if you fill out all 4, you get an extra $20 at the end of the surveys!Thank you all for participating! Victoria from TSP
It's already been 90 days? Wow.Thank you for doing this study. My eyes have been opened more and it has caused me to do research outside of the study.
Can't believe it's been ninety days already!

Hey TSP members! We just realized that we incorrectly stated that there are 5 surveys total - there are actually only 4. We've edited the message above so it is accurate now. Sorry about any confusion! Please let us know if you have any questions/concerns. Thanks! :)-Shirley from TSP

90.  Times they are a-changin’. Instead of endorsing smoking, Hollywood stars are now starting a new trend and quitting for their health. Check out this slideshow of all the actors and celebrities who have recently taken the dive and quit smoking! What do you think of this trend? #socialreflection http://www.shape.com/celebrities/celebrity-photos/10-celebrities-who-quit-smoking
It's a great trend. A lot of younger people look to these famous faces as role models
89.  Does hearing that rat poison is found in cigarettes change the way you feel about smoking? #beingconscious
I already knew that, so no.

88.  Your stroke risk is now the same as a person who never smoked, your risk of lung cancer has dropped to half that of a continual smoker, and your risk of coronary disease and death in general have returned to nearly the level of people who have never smoked before. How do you feel knowing that you’re not doomed to have cancer? #beingconscious

I'm not that concerned about cancer anyway, because these days pretty much everything gives you cancer. If it isn't lung cancer from smoking, it will be skin cancer from working outside, or colon cancer from not eating right, or breast cancer for no reason at all.
87.  Have you noticed more and more celebrities quitting smoking? Do you think this encourages more people to say goodbye to cigarettes? #socialreflection
I haven't because I don't really pay attention to celebrities, but I guess most people would follow what their favorite celebrities do.
I haven't noticed either. I'm sure if younger adults follow their celebrities as role models they would definitely notice.

86.  As a result of the 2009 Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act, tobacco companies have been banned from offering free samples and selling cigarettes in packages that contain fewer than 20 cigarettes. Why do you think that is? #beingconscious
Free samples can't be taxed, and selling them in packages less than twenty makes it much easier to afford, meaning it's easier to smoke.
With the 90 days being almost over I am curious to hear about your experience: What is the most important thing you have learned from TSP? #TDII
The most important thing I learned  would probably be just the dangers and tips on how to control cravings
Thanks for sharing 10229! How do you plan on using what you have learned going forward?
I've got to say the ways to control cravings
85.  Have you ever heard this statistic before? How many smokers do you know? Divide that number by three and that’s how many may die in the future from a smoking-related illness. #beingconscious
I have heard this. I know at least six smokers, probably a lot more

84.  Flavored cigarettes have been outlawed for years now, yet e-cig companies are using old tricks to gain new customers while they still can. Would you have been more likely to start smoking as a minor if the product you used was flavored like your favorite candy? #ecig
I could totally see how they are marketing to minors. My friend's daughter is 16 and bragging about how her e-cigarette tastes like cinnamon. And bubble gum. And watermelon.

data.message: 83.  In movies and TV shows, smoking used to be a popular prop to make characters seem more edgy or cool. Researchers and even some members of Congress are urging Hollywood to cut out smoking images targeting youth. Do you think smoking in movies should mean they get a R-rating? Why? #beingconscious
I think they should be rated stronger, but not to that degree. Smoking is not down much in newer films, and when it is, it's usually the bad guys.

54.  Quitting smoking can slow balding in men. Fellas, does this seem like a good reason to think about quitting? And ladies, how would this fact help you encourage your male loved ones to quit smoking?  #beingconscious
I would just tell them this and show them examples
Receding hairlines run in my husband's family. I'll definitely tell him this!
I've been balding since before I started smoking lol

53.  While ammonia helps keep our bathrooms and kitchens clean, it does anything but that for our lungs. Does learning it's found in cigarettes change the way you think or feel about smoking? #beingconscious
I already knew it was in cigarettes. I've known longer than I can remember that cigarettes have all kinds of chemicals that I don't need to inhale.
D.A.R.E. taught me this years ago.
51.  Why do you think hookah has held on to a 'cool' reputation even though it's just as unhealthy as other forms of tobacco use? #beingconscious
I have no idea...
Hookahs look cool too. Just like e-cigarettes. They are trendy. I didn't know that was the equivalent to 200 cigarettes. Hookahs dont have any warning labels.
I think it's because people don't smoke hookah like cigarettes
Yeah. And its a social thing really.

50.  FACT: People usually take two or three attempts to successfully quit for good. Aaliyah said it best: If at first you don't succeed, Dust yourself off and try again. Would you be able to try again? #beingconscious
Yes. Possibly sooner than I expected.
Yeah. I've tried 3 times.

82.  One year after a cigarette, the additional risk of coronary heart disease accumulated while smoking has decreased by half. AND the health of your gums and teeth have improved drastically. What other changes in your life would be present after not smoking for 365 days? #beingconscious

81.  As far back as 1969, tobacco companies have said they have “taken a great many steps to avoid advertising directed to young people”, but 10 years later, they arranged for their cigarettes to be featured in The Muppet Movie. What do you think about tobacco companies targeting young people through the media? #beingconscious

80.  It’s true, all the new tobacco legislation sure is making it harder to smoke. But have you ever turned it on its head? How is this new legislation making it easier for you to quit? What new laws or regulations would be really helpful to you if you decided to stop smoking? #socialreflection
79.  Coughing, sinus congestion, fatigue, and shortness of breath all decrease after this long without a cigarette. What can you do with a clear airway that you can’t do now? #beingconscious
Play my clarinet for more than ten or fifteen minutes
Do you think you will EVER be ready to quit smoking? Why? Why not? #TDII
Yes, I do. If I become pregnant again because I do not want to cause a health risk. Maybe when I am done with school because most hospitals do not hiring people who smoke
Hi 10229 - thanks for sharing. These are great reasons! How confident are you that you can quit successfully if you decide to try to?

Pretty confident. I quit cold turkey last time and I would have a reason to. Since I can't see the future results smoking has on me it gives me no motivation. I know what they are, I know how I would be living, but for some reason it doesn't click with me. If I quit today, I would not be able to.
I can see why long term consequences wouldn't be a big concern for you right now. Are there any short term effects you don't like about smoking? Smell, money, fertility?
I plan on quitting when I get pregnant.
Probably money because I am struggling, hiwever when I wasn't struggling I never noticed.
Since both of you mentioned getting pregnant I'm wondering if you are concerned about the effects of smoking on fertility (smoking makes getting pregnant harder) at all? What do you think about that?
I haven't heard of that. You might have left, but what about for men?
Great question 10229 - it affects both men and women. Check out this information: https://www.asrm.org/FACTSHEET_Smoking_and_Infertility/
I have to run. Great discussion today - I'll see you next week.
78.  Why might your smoking buddies want you to keep smoking? What are their motives? #socialreflection
None of my smoking buddies want me to keep smoking.

77. Anyone who smokes knows someone who wants them to quit. Think about the people in your life who want you to quit: why do they want this so badly for you? What types of arguments do they have? #socialreflection
My mom and my husband's grandpa want us to quit. They tell us what we already know: that it's bad for our health
My clients do. Especially the ones that smoke. They say they do not me to end up like them.With COPD, asthma, pneumonia, or bone cancer

76.  Every year it seems like there’s a new bill or law passed that’s tightening up the smoking legislation. What recent changes to tobacco laws in your community are making it harder for you to smoke? Do you think these new laws protect more people than they inconvenience? #socialreflection
I think they do protect a lot of people, but they do also inconvenience a lot of people. I don't really get or much so I haven't really noticed any new changes in my community

data.message: 75.  FACT: Treatments cost between $3-$10/day, and some health insurances cover medications and/or counseling. Would you spend a little more money to finally stop throwing cash down that bottomless cigarette-pit? Why do you think so many smokers don’t? #beingconscious
74.  When you're online, how is smoking portrayed on your favorite sites such as Facebook or YouTube? What messages are being sent online about smoking? #socialreflection
I don't see any. This study is the only time I've seen anything about smoking online in a long time
73.  Have you noticed how smoking is portrayed in magazines and advertisements? How do you feel about the way it's represented to the world? #socialreflection
I don't really see any cigarette ads, unless it's for ecigs. Those are presented as being cool and suave.
72.  Lots of people are bothered by the strong smell of nail polish remover, but did you know that anyone who smokes a cigarette is inhaling this chemical into their lungs? #beingconscious
I didn't know. That is interesting. I have never actually looked at a full list of 'ingredients' before.
I did not know that. I've never been bothered by the smell
Have you ever noticed a connection between smoking and your mood? Is there an emotional state that gets you to light up more frequently? #TDII
Sadness or boredom for me
If I'm angry I'll almost chain smoke.
Hi 10229 - yes, these are very common ones. What do you like to do for fun? Things that would help with boredom or sadness?
Hi 10253, for you the trigger is anger. Have you ever tried other things that calm you down other than smoking? How did it go?
Nothing I've tried has worked. I have to wait it out. Smoking doesn't work either, but it does keep me from getting violent.
10253 sounds like it's really all about buying you time until the anger goes away and cigarettes help you with that. What else have you tried?
I don't do anything, really.
10229, would you be interested in some suggestions for things to do?
Sure
Check this out 10229 - anything sound useful to you?
71.  How is smoking portrayed on TV? What have you noticed about characters who smoke on TV shows or in movies? #socialreflection
I never paid much attention. I grew up watching older movies when smoking was normal.
70.  Check out what Big Tobacco companies consider their 'Doomsday Scenario'. What do you think about what their records say? #socialreflection

They're a company. They lost a market. For them it is a doomsday scenario, because they might go under once their older market either stops smoking or dies. It's no different than if an alcohol company felt like young adults were no longer partying. They're losing income.

data.message: 69.  Check out this link to view which U.S. College Campuses and Universities have 100% Smoke-Free ordinances. Do you think it’s a good idea to make institutions of higher education smoke free? #socialreflection http://no-smoke.org/pdf/smokefreecollegesuniversities.pdf
Yes, I think it is a good idea. My community college is smoke free. They do a warning the first time and fines the next times.
I understand having designated smoking areas, but it doesn't make much sense for students who live on campus.
I didnt think about them banning it with people living on campus...would that even get enforced or would people follow that rule with so many young smokers?

68.  Many people don’t like to label themselves as a “smoker”. The fact remains that switching to an e-cig does not mean you’ve stopped ingesting addictive and harmful chemicals. And Big Tobacco would much rather you switch and remain a loyal customer, than deciding to quit once and for all. Have you ever felt like you had to hide your smoking? #ecig
No

67.  Your overall blood circulation has improved, walking has become easier, and your lung function has increased significantly. Have you noticed anything physical becoming more difficult as you smoke more? #beingconscious
Not really. But I've never really been an active person.

66.  Check out this link to see what the Tobacco Control Laws are like in your state. Be sure to know the smoking legislation if you plan on traveling. What do you think about the laws in your state. #socialreflection http://www.rwjf.org/en/library/research/2010/03/interactive-tobacco-map-provides-latest-data-on-state-smoking-la.html
65.  Have you noticed your sense of smell being impacted by your smoking? What different kinds of scents have you missed since you started smoking? #beingconscious
I haven't noticed a loss in any of my senses.
Have you ever tried to quit or reduce your smoking? Which strategy did you choose and how did it go? #TDII
I have tried cold turkey, using an e cig with no nicotine. The e cig lasted about four days, the cold turkey lasted almost two weeks.
Thanks for sharing 10253 - based on your experience, what would you recommend to someone who wants to quit? What are the most important things in your opinion?

Dedication, and being ready to quit. If you aren't ready it doesn't matter what method you try, or how determined you are, you'll most likely start smoking again. That's why neither method worked permanently for me.
I definitely agree with you 10253 - the motivation and dedication are crucial! What would get you more excited about quitting?
Knowing it will have a huge impact on the life of someone I love. That's how I'm so sure I'll be able to quit when I'm pregnant. The health of my children is more than enough motivation for me.

Yes this can be a great motivation for you. If you are serious about getting pregnant you may want to consider quitting even earlier. Did you know that smoking reduces the fertility of both women and men? What do you think about that?

I quit cold turkey. I had other things to think about and smoking made me extremely sick. It went well for nine months, and then I started back.I also tries for a day with an e-cigarette and I was continually smoking that.
Hi 10229 - so if you were ever ready to try quitting again in the future which strategy would you choose?

64.  Why do you think romantic partners have such a big impact on how much you smoke? If you’re in a relationship, what could your partner do to help you change your ways, and if not, would you be willing to quit smoking to begin a new relationship? #beingconscious
I started smoking because my husband had his where I could reach them. We are planning on quitting together.
Me and my boyfriend want to quit together. We might smoke more when we're together and bored.
63.  What would you do with those 18 days -- go on a trip? Stay home and finally watch that movie everyone’s been talking about? #beingconscious
I would probably go to Europe. Or maybe road trip around America

data.story: Johannes Thrul created an event for 2014-15 Not Ready to Quit Yet 6.
data.name: The Doctor Is In
data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: Hi everyone, the next Q&A session will be on Wednesday. See you then!

data.message: 62.  On average, smokers get sick more often than nonsmokers. How would work or school be different if you didn’t smoke? #beingconscious
Even though I smoke I almost never get sick, so it wouldn't make much difference.
60.  Who in your life would benefit if you decided to quit smoking? Think of all the people your smoking touches and comment on each other’s lists. #smokingaffectsall
My husband, my future children. I really can't think of anyone else.
No one really

61.  Since President Obama signed the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act into law, tobacco companies have been banned from brand sponsorship of sports and entertainment events. Do you think the fans at these events will miss their favorite Tobacco brands at their game or show? #socialreflection
Not at all.

To be completely honest, and yes I may be a little biased considering I do smoke; but I actually do not agree with the fact that tobacco companies have been banned from marketing or promoting their products. Why? Yes. Cigarettes are bad, we can all agree to that. But so is alcohol. So is many other products. This is America, where we have always believed in 'market freedom' free trade, and allowing businesses no matter how ridiculous to promote. That is what makes us great. Its the principal that now, if the government does not like some type of product, and can stir up enough support, can ban the promotion of a private product from many of the largest companies in the US. I disagree with the principal of that.

59.  FACT: Research shows that although some people quit cold turkey successfully, the most effective way to quit smoking is using a combo of counseling plus nicotine replacement therapy (NRT’s, like patch or gum) or medicine (like bupropion SR). What have you heard about NRT’s? Would you consider using them? #beingconscious
I hadn't heard much except that the gum tastes horrible. But I have no desire to use NRT.
I've heard of them, but since I was able to quit cold turkey I would do that again.I just wouldn't be able to do weaning off.

58.  Because your nerve endings have started to re-grow, your ability to smell and taste is enhanced. How much better does everything taste when you don’t smoke? Do you miss any of your favorite dishes? #beingconscious
I haven't noticed any change in how things taste or Angel, even when I managed to quit for two weeks.
What is currently your biggest smoking trigger? #TDII
Eating.
Hi 10253 - what do you like about smoking after a meal?
Mine is stress
It settles my stomach if I ate too much, and since I smoke menthols it cleanses my palate
Hi 10229, smoking helps you deal with stress. What else do you like about smoking?
10253 what other situations trigger smoking for you?
Stress, drinking coffee or alcohol, waking up...
And cleaning. Cleaning fumes bother me and smoking helps.
These are very common triggers 10253 - have you ever tried and experimented with things you could do to reduce an urge to smoke without actually smoking a cigarette?
I fidget and have anxiety. So smoking puts something in my hands to distract me and do absent mindedly.
I have, but I usually end up trying to chew a hole in my lip.
Same question for you 10229 - have you ever tried something else that may help with your anxiety? Something to keep your hands busy for example?
So what did you try 10253?
I've tried butterscotch candy, chewing on straws, I can't remember what else
Before smoking I would fidget with pens or actually chew on the end of my long sleeve shirts..Now the only thing I might do if I have no cigarette is play with my phone to have something in my hands.
Ah ok 10253, so these didn't help too much I take it. What you ever tried nicotine replacement at all? The gum for example?
No. I'm not a fan of nicotine replacement. The only thing that really worked at all was using zero nicotine juice in my e-cig

10229 - I was actually just going to suggest playing a game on the phone. Other options may be: Use a stress ball, play with a Rubik’s cube, start a fun arts and crafts project. Any of these sound like they may work for you?
10253 - very cool. So what did you do when you used your vape pen? Replaced the cigs? How long were you able to go without cigs?
I went about a week. And yes, whenever I felt like I needed a cigarette I would use my ecig. Unfortunately I wasn't quite ready and started bumming cigarettes from my neighbors.
When I was crocheting I smoked less. I wasn't using it to replace cigarettes, but for the most part it did.
That's very interesting 10253 - you just said you weren't ready back then. So what would have to happen so you would be more ready sometime in the future?

I think I would need a more pressing reason to quit. I'm already planning on quitting when I get pregnant, and since I'm trying it should be in the near future. I tried to quit last week because I thought I was pregnant and tested negative, but I only made it about a half a day.
It's great that you are trying 10253! How would you go about trying to quit next time? What strategy would you use?
Since I would be pregnant next time I quit, it would probably be cold turkey, to lessen the risks to the baby
57.  How do you think your life would change if you always smelled fresh and never like a cigarette? #balance
I don't know. The only time any one mentions it is my husband's grandfather.
I wouldn't have to hide it at ny job.
56.  The Wanted's band member Max George is photographed smoking all the time. How do you think this is influencing his fans’ ideas about tobacco? #beingconscious
I don't think it should at all.
Some people are like 'no one smokes anymore, it's gross.' But others would think 'hey, my role model is smoking...I should..he looks fit, healthy, and cool'

data.message: 55.  Hey ladies, did you know that quitting smoking can reduce the chances of ectopic pregnancy, miscarriage, still birth, and having a low birth weight baby? What do you think about this? Guys, how does knowing this make you feel about encouraging the women you love to quit smoking? #beingconscious
I was aware of these things, which is why my plan is to quit when I get pregnant.

I knew about this so I quit when I was pregnant, but started again after. I never smoke around her and when she was a newborn I changed my shirt and washed and hand sanitized my hands lol... I plan to stop again when I become pregnant again. Hopefully not start back.

52. Ever wondered how much $ you’ve spent on smoking so far? Use this smoking calculator and find out once and for all. Tell us what your number is and what you’d spend that on if you could get it back. #beingconscious
data.name: Cost Savings Calculator
data.caption: www.quitnow.net

data.message: $2730 a year. I knew I spent a lot, but not that much! That could have bought me a car!
$1105 for a year. Could pay off my debts if I got it back in a lump sum.
What do you guys like about smoking? #TDII
I'm a lot calmer
It gives me something to do and it helps in really stressful situations.
Thanks for sharing guys! Sounds like smoking helps both of you to de-stress and relax. Are there any aspects of smoking you don't like?
I've got to run - see you guys next week.

42.  What do you think middle school and high school nonsmokers are more likely to pick up: a cigarette, which they know are bad, smelly, and frowned upon, or a shiny, gadget-y, trend setting e-cig? Read this article to find out more about how under-aged kids are responding to the new e-cigs craze. #ecig http://www.cancer.org/cancer/news/electronic-cigarette-use-doubles-among-teenagers

I think teenagers would pick up the e-cigarettes. That's the trend now. Even one of my non-smoking friends that is in their early 20s has tried my e-cigarette that I am trying to get rid of. I think I would be great when they put the ingredients on them.

The e cig. I think they are aware that they are still addicting, but we tend to see e cigs as cleaner, healthier alternatives. I also have a friend, also early twenties, who has an e cig that he uses with non nicotine liquids.
E-cig. But I think its naivety that results in them picking one up. Not the fix for nicotine.

41.  A Dartmouth Medical study reported that adolescents who viewed smoking in movies were more than 50% more likely to smoke than those who didn’t watch smoking in movies. What do you think the younger generation is learning about tobacco and cigarettes? #beingconscious http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12892958?dopt=AbstractPlus
For the most part, I think they are being well educated on the risks involved. Those that choose to smoke do so in spite of the damage cigarettes cause
I was already interested in smoking by the time I started noticing it in movies.

40.  The carbon monoxide level in your blood drops down as the oxygen level in your blood increases back to normal. Have you ever noticed a difference in your breathing when you’ve been without a cigarette for 12 hours? #beingconscious
No
I have not noticed.
Nope
I dont think I've even gone twelve hours in the last year and a half.

39.  FACT: Just like with any other addiction, quitting can be difficult, and it might be hard to do it alone. Would you be able to get the support you need if you wanted to quit smoking? What would you try? #beingconscious
I would have support from all sides. I would probably quit cold turkey.
Cold turkey sandwhich. And I'd get plenty of support. My friends eould ridicule me or try to tempt me.

38.  In 2009, President Obama signed into law the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act. Part of this law bans all cigarettes that contain a characterizing flavor, including all fruit and candy flavors. Do you think it's a good thing to ban candy and fruit-flavored cigarettes? Who do you think this portion of the law is trying to protect? #socialreflection
I do agree with this law, it's too tempting for children to start smoking with sweet flavored cigarettes.
I agree, but I had no idea these even existed.

37.  Children of smokers are far more likely to start smoking than children of nonsmokers and children of ex-smokers. Were you brought up in a home where smoking was allowed? If so, how do you think this affected your decision to start smoking? If not, where do you think your attitudes about smoking originated? #beingconscious

My mom always smoked around me, and even though I pestered her to quit for years the temptation was always there. When I started smoking it felt natural. I do think that it was a big part of why I started.

Neither of my parents smoked in front of me. Although they both smoked on occasion, I never saw it. All my aunts and uncles smoked though, so I assume thats where I got it. Also, those gum cigerettes were awesome when I was a kid.

36.  Social situations can make it hard not to smoke, especially when alcohol is involved. Does alcohol affect your smoking? How would you change that if you wanted to cut down or quit? #beingconscious
Alcohol does affect my smoking. Whenever I am drinking to get drunk I would have to have no cigarettes handy or at a bar where you have to go outside to smoke.
Alcohol makes me chain smoke. However, I almost never drink, so I doubt it would affect my ability to quit smoking.
I smoke twice as much when I'm drinking. Three times as much when I'm drinking coffee lol

49.  Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately, studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studied strategies like counseling or Nicotine Replacement Therapy (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit. #ecig
I actually quit for almost a month using an e-cig with no nicotine juices.

data.message: 48.  For any of you that aren’t sure what an e-cig is, take a look at this FDA page explaining what they are and some of the controversy surrounding their regulations. Do you feel that if you were a minor, an e-cig would be more appealing and seem “safer” to try than a traditional cigarette? #ecig
I think I would, not only because there's no real smoke, but also because you can get liquids without any nicotine in them.

I probably would if I was a minor and have seen all the smoke trick videos. They are made to look cool and trendy. The commercials make them look sophisticated juat like old cigarette commericals used to do.

47.  Your chance of a heart attack has already decreased after only one day without a cigarette. Your body will thank you. What do you usually think of when considering being smoke free for a full day? #beingconscious
Honestly? How to avoid prison. I don't handle being smoke free very well
Yeah, I would think of all the risks that were being lessened by not smoking.
I usually think that I'm doomed. Something will go wrong.
46.  Have you heard any conflicting information about smokeless tobacco? How do you feel now knowing the truth? #beingconscious
I've never heard that they were safer. I was always fully aware that they carried the same risks.
I have not

44.  What’s your take on Big Tobacco? Do you defend tobacco companies, or do you side with those who are critical of Big Tobacco? What types of things have you heard about tobacco companies? #beingconscious
Don't really care

45.  Another part of the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act (signed into law by President Obama in '09) prevents tobacco companies from making health claims about any supposed “reduced risk” of any of their products that might encourage new smokers or discourage smokers from quitting. Do you think this is fair? #socialreflection
Yes
All for it

Hello everyone,After today, you will all be halfway through our 90 days of posts. I wanted to take a moment to thank you all for participating and commenting so we can get your opinions and feedback. You are all helping our study so much and we really appreciate you.Thanks again and have a great weekend,Victoria from TSP

43.  There are lots of Nicotine Replacement Therapies, or NRT’s, available over-the-counter: the patch, gum, lozenge, nasal spray, and inhaler. What have you heard about NRT’s? Would you ever consider trying them? #beingconscious
Tried patches, and gum. They both gave me sores
I don't want to try any NRT, because I will still be feeding my addiction.

Did you know that you can avoid almost all of the negative long-term health consequences of smoking if you quit before you are 30 years old? Does that change how you feel about smoking and quitting? #TDII
I've got to run guys - check out this study if you're interested http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsa1211128

We will respond when we get back though, so don't worry!Have a happy and safe 4th of July,Victoria from TSP
How does your smoking affect your loved ones, kids, or significant other? What do they think about your smoking? #TDII

34.  If you quit smoking, the amount of secondhand smoke present in your home will decrease immediately, keeping your pets safe. Post a pic of your pet if you have one. How much did you think about nearby animals when you lit up before? #smokingaffectsall
This is two of my babies. I have thought about smoking near my cats before, mostly because the tabby in this picture freaks out at the sight of a cigarette.
I smoke outside and my kitties stay inside.
35.  Tell us how you get rid of the smoky smell after a cigarette. #balance
I don't
Going into my clients house I pat my shirt with hand sanitizer lol. Because the smell of perfume bothers some. I use smelling lotions
Yup. Going into work.

data.story: Johannes Thrul created an event for 2014-15 Not Ready to Quit Yet 6.
data.name: The Doctor Is In
data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: Hi everyone, the next Q&A session will be on Wednesday. See you!

data.message: 33.  Being labeled as “the smoker” can be tough. Have you ever felt uncomfortable around people who don’t smoke? #balance
Not really. I grew up with the philosophy that what other people think of me doesn't matter.

I do feel uncomfortable, only because when I'm not smoking a cigarette and someone else is, the smoke is somewhat annoying to me. So when I'm smoking but no one else around me is, I feel awkward. I try my best to make my smoke go away from people, simply as a courtesy.

32.  Children can’t really distinguish between vapor and smoke. What they do see is important adults in their life setting an example for how to take care of themselves, what they spend their money on, and their attitudes about addictive substances. Would you hide your e-cig smoking from a child? #ecig
I probably wouldn't if I used one. They're are making it out that E-cigarettes aren't as bad.
Probably not.
I dont think I would. I rarely use mine, so the kids are never even around.

31.  Quitting smoking can help preserve our planet! Without cigarette smoke, the chances of household fires decrease and less secondhand smoke is added into the air we breathe. Can you think of any other environmental improvements that might result from less smoke? #beingconscious
Less byproducts from cigerette manufacturing as well as less cigarette butts on the ground.
Healthier plants
30.  Cats are exposed to secondhand smoke toxins through breathing in the smoke around them, AND when they groom themselves. How can we help Fifi stop smoking? #smokingaffectsall
Smoke outside
Yeah, smoke outside.
Smoke outside.
I smoke outside.

29.  It’s true, we all know quitting smoking is hard. But switching to another, more socially-acceptable way of ingesting nicotine won’t help you conquer your addiction. What would you rather do, take the easy way and switch to e-cigs, staying addicted and making these e-cig companies more money, or quit once and for all to live free of any level of nicotine-addiction? How would you “enjoy your life more”? #ecig
When I plan on quitting, I am going to cut nicotine out completely. I know I will enjoy life more because I won't be tied to an addiction.
i would quit once and for all.
I smoke my ecig occasionally. I wouldnt switch to it. But lately I've been limiting myself when it comes to how often I smoke.
28.  For which reasons would your children, real or imagined, thank you most for quitting smoking? #smokingaffectsall
A healthier future for them, a house that smells better, not having to risk losing their mother to cigarettes.
They get to play in thr yard when I smoke. So they probably wouldnt like it lol
I know stopping smoking is not easy. How confident are you that you could quit smoking if you tried? #TDII
I'm not sure. If I had no one smoking around me I might be able to.
Hi 10229 - I agree having other smokers around can be a big time trigger and only being around nonsmokers would help. What else would make you more confident?
Sorry I've got to run. Talk to you next week!
Sorry, just got the notification!

27.  Due to the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act, tobacco companies have been banned from outdoor advertising within 1,000 feet of school and playgrounds. Do you approve this portion of the Act? What do you think? #socialreflection
I do agree with this completely. Children are more impressionable and advertisements have a greater impact on them. They don't need to be exposed to cigarettes at all in my opinion.
Hell yes. I got started smoking way too early, I don't want anyone repeating my mistake
100% agree. If anything, they should be banned from ANY advertising.

data.story: Johannes Thrul created an event for 2014-15 Not Ready to Quit Yet 6.
data.name: The Doctor Is In
data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: I'll be doing another session Q&A this week. Looking forward to seeing you there!

data.message: 26.  Who in your life nags you about smoking? What are their reasons for feeling the way that they do? #smokingaffectsall

My mother. She smoked for thirty years and quit about the time I started high school, partly due to me pushing her. When I started she was very disappointed that I would smoke when I knew exactly what it can do to you.
My mother. It wasnt ever her thing so she cant understand why its mine.

25.  LADIES: Quitting smoking can reduce your risk of breast and cervical cancer. Does this seem like a good reason to think about quitting? Guys, does this seem like a reason to encourage female loved ones to quit? #beingconscious
I'm already planning on quitting in the future, but until I have an immediate reason to quit, I'd rather not deal with the stress.
I try to encourage my girlfriend to reduce her smoking. Its semi hypocritical but see smokes twice as much as me.

24.  Male-smokers: Quitting could reduce your risk for erectile dysfunction. What do you think about that? Ladies: would this fact inspire you to encourage your male loved ones to quit? #beingconscious
I would if I noticed a problem, but my husband has no issues at all.
I have no issues so :/
When it becomes a problem, I'll address it. Unless theres irreversible damage.
23.  Your blood rate decreases, your pulse rate drops, and the temperature of your hands and feet increases. Have you ever noticed these changes after smoking? #beingconscious
First cigarette of the day yes. After that nope.
No. My hands and feet are always freezing. Only thing I notice is my blood pressure dropping at night if I smoke right before bed.
Same. I notice it at night. I guess cause I'm active during the day.
22.  Do you have a family member or know someone who has been diagnosed with some form of cancer? How has their life changed? #balance
My grandmother died of colon cancer, one of my best friends is currently on chemo for lung cancer. She has almost no energy and she feels sick all the time.
Great grandfather had emphysema and died

My paternal grandmother died of bone cancer. She seemed to stay the same until she passed. My maternal grandfather died if lung cancer. He stayed the same too. He even smoked cigerettes in his hospital room while receiving treatment

21.  FACT: Nicotine is a very addictive drug. For some, it can be as addictive as heroin or cocaine. Have you ever had someone belittle the power of your addiction? What was it like? What did they say? #beingconscious
I've been told that it's all mind over matter and if I concentrate enough I can put down my cigarettes and never pick them back up.
^ I agree with her. The people that day that don't smoke so it honestly feels that they have no room to speak
'It's all in your head.' Um, the feeling I get when I ignore a craving is too powerful to be a mind game.
My Mother hates my smoking, so she constantly tells me to stop, as if I'm simply eating cereal.
What would you miss most if you quit smoking for good? #TDII
I don't think i would miss it at all
Wow that's interesting 10208 - if you wouldn't miss it what are your reasons for smoking then?

I can't stop smoking. It's not as hard if I wake up and don't smoke but about half way through the day my withdraws drive me crazy. When I have attempted to quit I would make it to being up 5 hours and without a cancer stick that feels impossible
10208 that really sounds like you have a strong motivation to quit, but you don't think it will work for you. Does that sound about right? What strategies to quit have you tried before?

You could say that. Cold turkey, nicotine gum and e-cig. I quit for about a month using the e-cig and stepped down the nicotine until it was at zero. I started smoking again when I lost the job I was working at that moment

Wow yeah that does sound stressful and like a major trigger. On the positive side: You were able to stop your nicotine intake entirely and that is something you can be proud of! That should also tell you that you will be able to do it again. We can work on strategies to quit and to prevent a relapse if you would like to. I am happy to support you!
I world like to quit again. I just need to get my first paycheck then pick up new atomizer and e-fluid
It's great that you want to try again! Have you given any though to trying nicotine replacement or other medication again at all?
Just the e-cig

Sounds good. Let me just say that from a scientific perspective we don't really know yet if e-cigs are the most effective way to quit, while NRT has proven effectiveness. (that's just because I feel like I have to give you comprehensive information). What you want to try is of course totally up to you and I will support you either way! Also, it sounds like the e-cig has worked out for you before, which is good. When do you think you will be ready to quit?
In a phone off weeks
Ok, sounds good! If you don't mind I will be checking in with you about that over the next couple of weeks. Do you have friends and family that know about your quit plans and can support you?
I've got to run. I'll check back with you next week. See ya!
19.  Can you relate to your best smoking buddy on anything other than smoking? #smokingaffectsall
Yeah, she and I consistently have discussions on a variety of topics, the fact that we smoke together is more or less irrelevant
Yeah. My only smoking buddy is my boyfriend. I have no more friends that smoke
I don't have 'smoking buddies'

My best smoking buddy would be my husband, so of course we have other things in common. We game, read, and watch movies together. But most of my friends smoke and we do so much more than smoke together.
My significant other is my 'best smoking buddy' sooo yeah, theres other topics.

20.  Big Tobacco is advertising E-Cigarettes as a safer and better way to smoke, but studies have shown that they still contain toxins, even without the smoke. Why do you think so many people who smoke are ready to adopt new products even before proper research on their safety has happened? #beingconscious
I used an e cig for a while because it tasted better. I could choose whatever flavor I wanted.
The cool kids smoke vapors, tho. And they do cool smoke tricks. While watching one guy do smoke tricks at the bar, I thought I should get one lol
Better taste, cheaper in the long run and no need for a lighter lol
Outta sight, outta mind. Once long term effects have been studied, thingsvwill change.

data.description: Hi guys, I will take over the TDII sessions from this week onward.You can ask me everything you want to know around smoking, quitting, and the Tobacco Status Project.  See you Wednesday from 6-7 pm (Pacific Time) if you'd like. I look forward to meeting all of you!

data.message: 18.  Do you ever have to hide smoking? How does that affect you? #balance
Not now. I did when I first started because I didn't want my mom to know. It didn't really affect me much at all.
Nope. When I first started yes... I was 12 and my folks were pissed.... I got the typical smoke a whole carton punishment
I never had to but I decided to for some reason.
Sometimes at my job. I keep hand sanitizer handy, spray, and use excuses to go outside.
17.  Is there someone in your life that you'd be proud to tell that you quit smoking? What do you think they would say? #smokingaffectsall
My mom, my sister, my husband.. Lots of people would be proud of me. A lot of then would say 'about damn time'
My father. He'd probably congratulate.
16.  Would your life be different if others’ first impression of you was not smoky? #balance
Not really
I don't think so. I've never had anyone mention it.
I work in people's houses and assist people, so yes.
If I have, they havent mentioned it.

15.  Most people who smoke report dealing with stress as their top reason for smoking. Work, class, family, friends, significant others -- it can be a lot! Can you think of another way to deal with stress that doesn’t involve lighting up when things get tough? What could you do instead? #balance
Meditate. Deep breaths, yoga every day
I can't think of something that would help me, except eating :(
I cant think of anything. Eating and or sleeping.

Hi Everyone, I am switching things up and doing The Doctor Is In a bit later this week. What are people dealing with this week? Has anyone in this group ever tried to quit smoking before? If so, how did it go? If not, why not?

I'm about to head to bed, but I wanted to comment. I quit for nine months during my pregnancy. It made me sick and I didn't want to risk my baby's health. After a month she was born, I started back and then was diagnosed with ppd.

thanks for sharing right before bed, 10229. Your baby can continue to be a motivator for you not to smoke. If it worked once, it can work again…I hope you can find a good way to use that. I also hope you have some good help to treat depression.

I like to leave you guys with tips in these session, so today, here is our 5-step TSP quit plan. See if something resonates with you: 1. GET READY.• Set a quit date and stick to it – not even a single puff! 2. GET SUPPORT AND ENCOURAGEMENT.• Tell your family, friends and coworkers you are quitting.• Talk to your doctor or other health care provider.• Get group, individual, or telephone counseling. Think about who can support you with quitting smoking3. LEARN NEW SKILLS AND BEHAVIORS.• When you first try to quit, change your routine.• Reduce stress.• Distract yourself from urges to smoke.• Plan something enjoyable to do every day.• Drink a lot of water and other fluids. Think about which of these will be most helpful to you?4. GET MEDICATION AND USE IT CORRECTLY.Talk with your health care provider about which medication will work best for you:• Medication: bupropion, verenicline (prescription).• Nicotine Replacement:-gum and patch are over-the-counter-inhaler and nasal spray are prescriptionIs there one of these that you think would be helpful for you?5. BE PREPARED FOR RELAPSE OR DIFFICULT SITUATIONS.• Avoid alcohol.• Be careful around other smokers.• Improve your mood in ways other than smoking.• Eat a healthy diet and stay active.
Next week Johannes Thrul will be back. It has been a pleasure to do these sessions in the past few weeks, thanks everyone!
Just wanted to post my motivation, guys. My new job has offered me $100 in reimbursement for stop smoking products. Also a $100 reward if I do quit!
That's awesome
14.  How could you have a more active lifestyle without smoking? #balance
I could play my clarinet easier. I know it isn't exactly active, but I'm not exactly an active person.
Maybe running longer.
Football. I played a game recently and felt like my heart was gonna explode from my chest.
I think I'm pretty active, drum corps is extremely physical.
Not really
13.  Post your wish list here! #balance
A car
Probably music gear.

data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: We're switching it up again! This time, we're hosting our TDII session a little later in the evening. Come chat with Dr. @[100004013084694:2048:Danielle Ramo] for some great advice!

data.message: 12.  Yesterday we asked you to tell us how confident you were that you COULD quit smoking if you wanted to. What would it take to get you from the number you said yesterday to ONE NUMBER HIGHER? #motivation
I'm entirely (a 9 on the scale) confident I could quit, I just enjoy cigarettes a little too much to quit right now
Getting pregnant
I agree getting pregnant or getting a job where they test for cigarettes
10.  What is keeping quitting smoking from the top of your priorities list? What would make quitting even more important to you? #motivation

Arguing with my husband. Every time we try to go without cigarettes it puts a huge strain on our relationship and neither one of us is able to work through it yet. It will become much more important one we start our family.
Lack of motivation
11.  We understand that stopping smoking is not easy. On a scale of 1-10, how confident are you that you COULD quit smoking if you tried? #motivation
It depends on whether or not my husband and I argue. If we do, 2. If not, 7.
6. I dont have the motivation right now.
2 its gonna be extremely hard
9.  On a scale of 1-10, how important is it to you to quit smoking for good? #motivation
Right now its a 5 because right now I just have future plans. Soon it'll be a 10.
I agree with 10229. It's not really important to me right now, but it's a 10 to quit before I have children
Yeah, i quit whenever I was pregnant. But I started again when she was born mainly because of ppd. When I have another child, I might just quit for good.

Since stress is coming up a lot today, I want to leave you guys with a post about visual imagery that can help if you are having cravings to smoke and don't want o (or can't). As an experiment this week, try this and see if it can be helpful to you.
Hi Everyone, I'm here for the next hour to answer any questions or chat about smoking and quitting. What have been your biggest triggers to smoke lately?
It's after I eat. Very stressful situations. When I'm bored. When  I drink. Lol
All of those are very common triggers. Have you ever tried to avoid smoking in any of those situations, even as an experiment or because you couldn't? What happened?

Since stress is one of the more common triggers to smoke, I want to share a stress quiz in case anyone is curious about their level of stress: https://ucsf.co1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_a4bsPIqLQjDxSrH
When I wake up. That's the hardest cigarette for me to let go of

I have, actually. When I'm doing something I start to lose focus on it, I start feeling dizzy. There's also this feeling in the back of my mouth. Really those cravings make me feel like I'm having an out of body experience. Can anyone else relate to that lol? Cleaning is the only thing I can do that takes my mind off it, but I have to start cleaning before the cravings start and then barely notice them when they start.

That is another common one 10253. One strategy that sometime helps people if they are interested in reducing the cigarettes they smoke or quitting is to push that first cigarette just a bit later each day. What do you think might happen if you tried that (or have you)?
I have the same triggers. I have avoided smoking at those times on occasion, just to see if I can. I didnt really get cravings after I made up my mind not to.
I've noticed that too. If I'm really busy with something I won't notice a craving, but as soon as I slow down it hits all at once
Also, I suddenly wanna smoke a cigarette when I see someone in a movie or show smoking one. Im curious to know if this happens to anyone else?

Experiments can be helpful because they can sometimes help us to realize we could get through a trigger without smoking when we didn't think we could. I urge everyone to try some type of experiment  this week if you can. I once challenged a guy who swore he could not quit for one day to do so and much to his surprise, we was able to do it quite successfully.
If I push my first cigarette back I can't breathe properly until I do smoke (I smoke menthols) and one I do I get really lightheaded, like when I go a few days without a cigarette.
10279, you're not alone. As soon as someone on tv lights up I'm reaching for my cigarette case. Even if I just put one out.
I could try. I forgot to name my biggest one - talking on the phone to someone. Ive noticed every time someone calls I head outside to smoke. I could try an experiment where I don't lol.
Yeah it registers 'hey he's smoking' and then I debate myself for a little bit on whether I want to.
Yes that is a good example! Or next time you take a call. DON'T go outside. Take it somewhere you can't smoke, ideally. See how that goes this week...
Also, if I push my first cigarette back too far the craving hit and I start getting a little twitchy and very very angry.

Some info you guys may be interested in about smoking in movies: http://www.legacyforhealth.org/our-issues/smoking-in-movies It's a trigger for smokers and also increases likelihood that kids start smoking when they see smoking in movies.

Cravings are a doozy!  One thing to remember for all of you guys is that cravings only last about 2-5 minutes, and then they reduce so you just need some strategies to get you through those few minutes  when they are particularly tough. Strategies are to remind yourself why you don't want to smoke right now, picture your reason to quit, distract yourself, take a walk, chew gum, etc. I could do this all day but the key is for you to find some strategies that will work for you.
Hi Everyone, I'm here for the next hour to answer any questions or chat about smoking and quitting. What have been your biggest triggers to smoke lately?
Stress honestly
That is probably the most common trigger for smoking. Have you ever tried anything to manage stress other than smoking? Has anything been successful?
I have tried other things for stress management but they typically don't work when you need a cigarette.... I quit for about two months and started again when I lost my good paying job
The challenge there is that I am sure that was a time when it was hard to spend more $$ on cigarettes. Good for you to have quit for the 2 months. WHat worked to help you stay smoke free that long?
An E-Cig with no nicotine and playing music. Anything to distract me from withdraws and strong urges to smoke

Distraction can be a very good thing when you are quitting. E-cigs are a mixed bag. Some arguments say that having them can be triggering because they mimic a cigarette, but great that it worked for you - especially if there was no nicotine. How are you feeling now about smoking, I take it that you are smoking again, which is why you are here. When do you think you might be ready to quit again?
Well I am in the process of moving, unpacking and finding a new job.... I may be quitting real soon due to lack of money

As hard as that is, if it helps you to quit that may be a good thing. In some ways, the move may help as well - it is a different environment where you will not be used to smoking. A clean slate, so to speak...
Good point. I'm not sure if I would be able to handle that. I am defiantly going to try
defiantly, or definitely? Perhaps a freudian slip there ;) Quitting is not easy but it actually sounds like you are motivated. Why do you want to quit?
The smell and the film on my car windows. Weird reasons right?

No reason is weird. The more personal the better because they matter to you and will be impactful when you are ready. I hear a lot about cars being triggers and also motivators to quit because they are tight environments. When you quit, it will be important to clean your car, completely and totally. Did you try that last time?
I did and I filled the ash tray with baking soda and some laundry detergent.
Good ideas. Deodorize like crazy. How was it to be in your car without the smell or other effects of smoking when you were quit?
Nicer to drive and easier to clean haha

Well good! Use that when you are thinking about quitting this next time around and remind yourself of what it will feel/look/smell like to have your car like that again. Another strategy that might help you is adding up the $$ spent on smoking to see how much you will save if quit. Here's a simple costs calculator I like: http://smokefree.gov/savings-future
alright :)
Great, good luck, with everything you are dealing with. It may also help to set a quit date if you feel ready.
8.  Do you think you will ever want to quit smoking? If yes, when? #motivation
Yes. I intend to quit before I have children, so they don't grow up around it.
Yes I do plan on quitting smoking when I am in a better possition and learn to manage my stress better then I am able to at this moment in time
eh, maybe some day, I dont really have any problems as I currently sit in regards to it, if that changed maybe I would.
Whenever I start smoking more than a pack a week.
Its somewhere in my five year plan.
Eventually, probably when I have kids
Probably later. If i get to a pack a day, that will be a problem later.

data.description: Hello TSP members! Based on your responses to our poll, we've decided to keep the same time as last week (4-5pm PDT). We hope that you can join Dr. @[100004013084694:2048:Danielle Ramo] at today's session!

data.message: 7.  How would you react if you found out your son or daughter smoked cigarettes?  #motivation
I'd be pissed at myself
Yeah, right? Like everyone my age I know that smokes - their parents smoke. I feel like it would be my fault because she sees me doing it whenever we are outside. She would think it's the norm.
I completely agree. My husband and I were both raised by smoking parents. He started smoking at twelve and I started at eighteen. I would be really mad at myself, and my husband.
I would feel at blame, but depending on the age, I would tell them not to lie to me about it and accept the conciquinses that come along as well as advise on the horrible side effects.
6.  What’s the worst thing that could happen if you don’t quit smoking? #motivation
I could get lung cancer
Spend more money
Like 10253 said about cancer, air could become diagnosed with diseases that are not treatable. Even diseases that are treatable, would still be one of the worse things that could happen.
Well. The obvious answer. I could die.
Getting throat cancer. Or that one where there's a hole in your neck. I can't remember the name but it sounds horrible.
5.  What would be the best-case scenario if you quit smoking? #motivation
I would save money, and be able to raise my children in a healthier environment.
Agree save money. I would be healthier. My risk of cancer, blindness, and living with a hole in my throat would decrease.
Save money and have better cardio
4.  What was your reason for picking up that first cigarette? Was it to be cool, to be independent, to experiment, to look older, or something else? #beingconscious

I was trying, and failing, to cope with dropping out of college for financial reasons, and getting everything ready to move back home, and my husband was smoking on the couch next to me. I just grabbed one of his.
Mine was...interesting... Lol the story and reason behind it would take too long to explain. In basic form it was because I needed something to do you could say.
All my friends were doing it and made no big deal about it. Having parents that smoked, it was easy for all of us to sneak them.
I was 12 and my older cousin and I started smoking to cover up the smell of something else
3.  How would you support someone who tells you they want to quit smoking? #motivation
Mental and stress support
Emotional and mental support. 'Oh, you're quitting? Good. Don't continue making the mistake I am.'
Id definitely provide moral and mental/stress support. As well id encourage them to change their habits so they arent around smokers for a period of time to help prevent them from wanting to smoke.
I wouldn't smoke around them, is congratulate them on a tough decision and give them any mental and emotional support they need.
I would give them 800-quit smoking number. I wouldn't smoke around them. I would give them support and help motivate them.
Definitely wouldn't smoke around them. And provide any sort of support they require.
2.  What are some of your favorite qualities about yourself?  How does smoking fit (or not fit) with that image of you? #balance
My adaptability is my favorite quality about myself. Smoking helps cope with the stress of new things

Im told all the time that my first impression on people is that I'm kind and polite person. Im sure I lose brownie points when they see me smoking.Also I'm in my early twenties, however I look 15. I should be flattered by looking younger, but one reason I smoke is to make myself look older.
I'm often told I'm very humorous. I can make light of situations with laughter. Problem is, after telling a joke I laugh and expose my yellow teeth. It leaves me feeling self cosciencse about it.
I'm a very healthy person, except for the smoking, and I'm very patient and smoking helps me stay that way.
Probably my personal integrity, as well as my ability to stay head strong despite obstacles.
1.  Share a success that you have had in the past. It can be anything from any time. Why did it work? Who helped you? #motivation
The soonest one.. Replaced my brakes. It worked because I was able to read a repair manual and no one actually helped
Teaching my son to say mom. It worked because i worked with him everyday and my family along with my fiance helped me.
Potty training my daughter. It worked because we kept at it and sent a list with her to her grandparents house. Gummy bears played a role in helping it work. My boyfriend and her grandma helped me.

I graduated high school, despite depression and extreme stress my senior year. It worked because I had the support of some very awesome people, including my husband and my amazing school guidance counselor.
My band played a show to at least 100 people. The biggest crowd I've played. We won the battle of the bands because of all our rehearsal. I couldn't have done it without my band mates.
I played lead clarinet for the college that I had graduated from. It was a lot of hard work to learn all of my solos but I was ready by the time we had our concert. All 5,000 seats were filled.
I was on the Dean's list at my university last semester. My mom and boyfriend are always supportive. I also had a great advisor who helped make it possible for me to graduate next year.

Hi Guys, welcome to TSP! In addition to daily posts, we also have weekly sessions with a live person who can talk to you about smoking. It's usually Johannes Thrul, but today you are getting me. I am an Assistant Professor of Psychiatry at UCSF in San Francisco and creator of TSP. Happy to answer any questions you have - I'm here for an hour.
Hi! My first question is: How long has TSP been going on?
Not long enough! JK, about a year and a half now all together. We have a series of studies that have involved TSP in some way.
10229 what got you interested in TSP?
I saw the post about doing the survey and I became interested. Its in my future to sometime quit and I was thinking this study may help me sooner by opening our eyes to more facts.
What gave you the idea for TSP?
Cool. We definitely talk about facts here. And also ask you to explore some things about your own smoking. For example, what are the reasons you may want to quit and why would it be hard?

I have been working in the field of substance use (tobacco and other drugs) for a while, and I realized that social media is a good way to reach people who may want to change but need some help, or are not sure if they want to change
Heya, my question is What kind of results or information are you hoping to get out of the study?

Hi 10248 we want to to figure out if delivering a program like TSP through social media can impact behaviors and attitudes about smoking and quitting. I know, pretty broad, right? This is a very new type of project, so there are still a lot of uninsured questions. Why did you get involved?
More or less just a general sense of intrigue, no particular desire to quit at this point but always glad to help a study.
Cool, well were glad you're here! Hopeful hit will be a good experience. Do you think you might want to quit one day? Just curious...
Gotta run guys, but I will be here two more weeks and we can follow-up on anything else you are thinking about or questions before our regular counselor Johannes Thrul is back. Great chatting today!
